Morning
.
I have just read thy letter again, Edward. It is
hardly
light enough yet, to see the characters that I trace with
my pencil; and it is exceedingly cold; yet, here I am,
sitting
up in my bed; my port folio before me; and the cold
day-light shining on the paper, with a feeble and sickly
lustrepoh!I will be in better spirits. I will answer
thee, as I would that thou shouldst me, had I written
thee such a letter as thine. Soaway with all
despondency
and complaint. For awhile, I will be proud of
heart, and forget that I am in a land of strangers,
hapless
and aloneguiltyO God!and, perhaps, even now,
now
